          <change when="2021-03-03T07:17:35-05:00"
                 who="http://papyri.info/editor/users/james.cowey">General - The new reading τὰ [ἀ]βάσκαντά certainly looks very good. No sign of this elsewhere (BL) as far as I can see. μεθʼ ὧν εἶ looks pretty good. The form of the nu of ὧν is unusual for this hand (perhaps the nu in ἡμερῶν in lin11 is vaguely comparable). That the upper part of the epsilon is joined to an iota is good. The lower part of the epsilon would be formed by the final part of the preceding nu. </change>
          <change when="2021-03-03T07:02:14-05:00"
                 who="http://papyri.info/editor/users/ngonis">Vote - Accept-Straight-to-Finalization - τὰ [ἀ]βάσκαντά agreed (someone else might dot τὰ and the first ά, but it 's fine as it is; on photo =&gt; image). || Worth recording εἶ as an alternative in lin23. || Revise number tags in lines 3, 12 and 21 to remove superfluous spaces.</change>
          <change when="2021-03-03T02:48:55-05:00"
                 who="http://papyri.info/editor/users/nikos">Submit - l. 23 ἀσπάζου .2[.1].3 πάντ[α] σου παιδία → ἀσπάζου τὰ [ἀ]βάσκαντά σου παιδία&#xD;
                    &lt;:τὰ [ἀ]βάσκαντά=PN N. Litinas (on photo)|ed|.2[.1].3 πάντ[α]:&gt;&#xD;
&#xD;
The letters are clear. Only the first α of αβασκαντα cannot be seen on photo.&#xD;
&#xD;
&#xD;
In addition, it seems that ἔ[σ]η at the end of l. 23 is not certain. I think we should read εἶ  (= with whom you are), with an epsilon made in three (and not two, as in the same hand) strokes. This proposal has not been entered, but I will it open. </change>
